# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1994-seattle-mariners-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1976-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] The **1976 Major League Baseball Expansion draft** was held November 5, 1976.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1976-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] This expansion draft was conducted by Major League Baseball to stock the major league rosters of the Toronto Blue Jays and the Seattle Mariners, new American League franchises established via the 1977 Major League Baseball expansion that were set to start play in the 1977 season.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1976-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] Seattle was promised a franchise by Commissioner Bowie Kuhn.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1976-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] During the summer of 1975, there was speculation that the Minnesota Twins, Chicago White Sox, or San Francisco Giants could move to Seattle.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1976-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] When none of these plans proved successful, the American League added a team in Seattle.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1976-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] With 13 teams in a league creating scheduling problems, the league awarded a franchise to Toronto over Washington, D.C. in March 1976.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1976-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] Both Seattle and Toronto had purchased or otherwise acquired a handful of players shortly before the draft, but nowhere near enough to fill a roster (or even assemble a nine-man squad).
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1976-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] Drafted players were selected only from American League teams, in keeping with the practices of the American League expansion of 1961, the National League expansion of 1962, and the expansion of both leagues in 1969.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1976-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] Beginning with the next expansion, in 1993, the new teams would select players from teams in both leagues.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1976-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] Danny Kaye, part-owner of the Mariners, announced the club's first selection.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The **1977 Major League Baseball expansion** resulted in the establishment of expansion franchises in Seattle and Toronto in the American League of Major League Baseball.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Seattle Mariners and Toronto Blue Jays began play in the 1977 season, becoming the 25th and 26th teams in Major League Baseball.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Seattle and Toronto were included in a list of potential expansion cities in a survey conducted by the American League in 1960.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Seattle Pilots only played one season, during which they faced financial difficulties stemming from a complete lack of television coverage, a poorly performing team, a stadium with problems, and the highest ticket and concession prices in the league.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Owners of other American League teams wanted Dewey Soriano and William R.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Daley to sell the team to a Seattle owner who would improve the team and address issues at Sick's Stadium, particularly uncovered seats with bad views.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Selig had negotiated a deal for the purchase with Soriano during Game 1 of the 1969 World Series.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] As a result of the relocation of the Seattle Pilots to Milwaukee, in 1970 the city of Seattle, King County and the state of Washington sued the American League for breach of contract.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The $32.5 million lawsuit proceeded until 1976, when at trial the American League offered the city a franchise in exchange for the city, county, and state to drop the suit.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] On November 2, 1972, King County had broken ground on the Kingdome, which would come to be used by the Seattle Mariners for baseball and by the Seahawks for football.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] On January 15, 1976, the expansion franchise was approved, becoming the 13th franchise in the American League.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] It was owned by Lester Smith and Danny Kaye, who paid an expansion fee of US$6.5 million.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Owing to the history surrounding the franchise, sportswriter Emmett Watson of the Seattle Post-Intelligencer joked that the team should be named the *Seattle Litigants*.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Toronto had a long history of interest in baseball.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Its first professional baseball team was established in 1885, and in 1886 Sunlight Park was built to host its games.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] In 1897, Hanlan's Point Stadium was built at the Toronto Islands for the Toronto Maple Leafs of the International League, and on September 5, 1914 it was the site of baseball legend Babe Ruth's first professional home run and only minor league home run.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] In 1926, Maple Leaf Stadium was built for the Toronto Maple Leafs.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The team was successful, sometimes drawing more fans than established Major League Baseball teams.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The team was owned by Jack Kent Cooke, who in the mid-1950s sought municipal financing of a major league baseball park on the grounds of the Canadian National Exhibition.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] He was also involved in the failed attempt to establish the Continental League as a third league in Major League Baseball in the early 1960s.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Maple Leaf Stadium was demolished in 1968 after the Toronto Maple Leafs were sold to Walter Dilbeck and moved to Louisville, Kentucky.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] In the early 1970s, Toronto City Council alderman Paul Godfrey proposed a plan for a publicly financed domed stadium in the city, but it was opposed by taxpayers and amateur sports groups.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Undeterred, he proposed renovation of Exhibition Stadium to support baseball.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The stadium was renovated in anticipation of the city being awarded a Major League Baseball team, costing CA$15 million.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Half of the funds were provided by the municipal government, and the other half from an interest-free loan from the provincial Government of Ontario.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Its seating capacity was increased to 40,000.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] There had been strong interest from several groups and individuals to own a Major League Baseball team in the city.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The most prominent was Labatt Brewing Company, who wanted to use ownership of a sports team as a means to establish a visible presence in the Toronto market.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Giants had failed to repay a US$500,000 loan from Major League Baseball, and had experienced declining revenues since the relocation of the Kansas City Athletics to Oakland in 1968.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Of the sale price, US$5,250,000 was to be placed in escrow to "meet certain possible obligations with respect to the transaction", especially the lease of Candlestick Park, which would expire in 1994.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The new owners of the Giants, led by Don McDougall, would move the team to Toronto pending approval from the other eleven National League teams, which would be sought on January 14 at the Winter Meetings of General managers in Phoenix.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The team would be known as the Toronto Giants and would begin play during the 1976 Major League Baseball season.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The deal was scuttled by a Superior Court of California, which issued an injunction blocking the sale on February 11, 1976; the injunction was requested by the city of San Francisco on January 10.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The National Exhibition Company eventually accepted a purchase proposal from Bob Lurie in a deal brokered by George Moscone, the Mayor of San Francisco; Lurie elected to keep the team in San Francisco.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] This was the third scuttled attempt by Labatt to bring an MLB team to Toronto, after failures to acquire the Baltimore Orioles and the Cleveland Indians.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Soon after, Godfrey received a phone call from Kansas City Royals owner Ewing Kauffman informing him that he supported a Toronto franchise for the American League.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] During an owners meeting held on March 20, 1976, the American League franchises voted 11-1 to expand the league with a Toronto franchise, to which National League owners resolved to consider a Toronto franchise to begin play in the 1977 season.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Bowie Kuhn, at the time the Commissioner of Baseball, planned for the National League to expand with new franchises in Toronto and Washington, D.C., and for the American League to add a new franchise in New Orleans in addition to the already-awarded Seattle franchise.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] On March 29, National League owners met and voted in favour of the expansion plans, but they were rejected because the vote was not unanimous, with dissenting votes from the owners of the Cincinnati Reds and Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] A subsequent vote on April 26 ended this plan with a 7–5 result in favour of the proposal, again failing to achieve unanimity.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Two groups bid for the rights to franchise ownership in the city, which presented bids during an American League owner's meeting on March 26, 1976.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Ultimately, an ownership group named Metro Baseball Ltd. consisting of Labatt Brewing Company, the Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce, and Imperial Trust won the bid for a franchise fee of CA$7 million.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The other bid was made by Atlantic Packaging.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The winning bid was represented by legal counsel Herb Solway and Gord Kirke.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Kirke prepared the original documents which led to the foundation of the team in 1976.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] After the city was awarded the franchise, U.S.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] President Gerald Ford attempted to pressure Major League Baseball to instead award the franchise to Washington, D.C., which he claimed should have a team before Toronto.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Both the American League and National League dismissed his request.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] In 1974, the Toronto City Council approved a further CA$2.8 million for renovations to Exhibition Stadium, retrofitting the stadium for baseball and would be ready in time for the 1977 season.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Paul Beeston was hired as the team's first employee on May 10, 1976, and Peter Bavasi was hired as the team's first president and general manager on June 18, 1976.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] In order to stock the roster of each team, a draft was held on November 5, 1976 in which each of the extant teams would make available to the expansion franchises some of the players on their major league and minor league rosters.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] Each team was allowed to protect fifteen players on the major league roster, and an additional three players after each of the first and second round of the draft.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-expansion] The Seattle Mariners and Toronto Blue Jays each selected 30 players in the draft.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The **1977 major league baseball season** began on April 6 while the regular season ended on October 2.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Cincinnati Reds from the 1976 season.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The 48th All-Star Game was held on July 13 at Yankee Stadium in New York, New York, home of the New York Yankees.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The National League won, 7–5, and was the sixth win in what would be a 10-win streak that lasted until 1983.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The season saw the fourth round of expansion (and third for the American League) since the beginning of the expansion era in 1961.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] While the National League voted at the same time as the American League to expand over the 1976 off-season, the National League did not have the necessary unanimous results to expand.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The league would not expand to 14 teams until 1993 when the Colorado Rockies and Florida Marlins were enfranchised.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The 1977 schedule consisted of 162 games for all 14 teams in the American League and 12 teams in the National League.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] For the first time since 1961, the two leagues saw different schedule formats.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The American League was split into two seven-team divisions.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 15 games against their six division rivals, totaling 90 games, and 10 games against five opponents and 11 games against two opponents, totaling 72 interdivision games.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the National League was split into two six-team divisions.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 18 games against their five division rivals, totaling 90 games, and 12 games against six interdivision opponents, totaling 72 games.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1969 and would continue to be the format in use until 1993.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 6, featuring four teams.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 2, featuring all 26 teams.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The National League Championship Series took place between October 4 and October 8, while the American League Championship Series took place between October 5 and October 9.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 11 and October 18.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 4 and ended on October 18 with the New York Yankees defeating the Los Angeles Dodgers in the 1977 World Series in six games.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] The Montreal Expos leave Jarry Park Stadium (where they played for eight seasons) and opened Olympic Stadium, where they would go on to play for 28 seasons through 2004.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] ABC aired *Monday Night Baseball* and the World Series.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-major-league-baseball-season] NBC televised the weekend *Game of the Week*, the All-Star Game, and both League Championship Series.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-seattle-mariners-season] The **1977 Seattle Mariners season** was the first season in franchise history, which was established via the 1977 Major League Baseball expansion.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-seattle-mariners-season] The creation of the Mariners brought baseball back to Seattle, which had been without a major league team since the Seattle Pilots left for Milwaukee to become the Brewers in April 1970.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1977-seattle-mariners-season] The Mariners ended the 1977 season by narrowly avoiding last place (held by the Oakland Athletics), finishing sixth in the American League West with a record of 64–98 (.395), 38 games behind the AL West champion Kansas City Royals.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1978-seattle-mariners-season] The **1978 Seattle Mariners season** was the second in franchise history.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1978-seattle-mariners-season] The Mariners ended the season by finishing last in the American League West with a record of 56–104 (.350), their first last place finish and six games worse than their inaugural season.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1978-seattle-mariners-season] After fielding only one minor league affiliate in 1977, the Mariners added a Triple-A and Single-A team in 1978.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1979 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the 50th playing of the midsummer classic between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and National League (NL), the two leagues constituting Major League Baseball.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] It was held on Tuesday, July 17, at the Kingdome in Seattle, Washington, the home of the third-year Seattle Mariners of the American League.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The National League won 7–6 for their eighth consecutive win.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game featured memorable defensive play by starting right fielder Dave Parker, as he had two assists on putouts: one at third base in the seventh inning and another at home plate to end the eighth.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] With Parker receiving the MVP award for this game, and teammate Willie Stargell winning the National League MVP, NLCS MVP, and World Series MVP, all four possible MVP awards for the season were won by members of the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was also notable for the play of Lee Mazzilli, providing the margin of victory.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In his only All-Star appearance, Mazzilli tied the game in the eighth inning with a pinch hit home run off of Jim Kern of the Texas Rangers, and then put the National League ahead for good in the ninth, drawing a bases-loaded walk against Ron Guidry of the New York Yankees.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] This was the only All-Star Game at the Kingdome.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] When it returned to Seattle in 2001, the Mariners had moved across the street to their new home at Safeco Field.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] It was the second All-Star Game held indoors, the first was eleven years earlier at the Astrodome in Houston.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The weather outdoors was unseasonably hot in Seattle, with a high temperature of 96 °F (36 °C).
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Players in *italics* have since been inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] American League starter Nolan Ryan began the game in sizzling fashion, striking out Davey Lopes and Dave Parker, but walked Steve Garvey.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Mike Schmidt tripled in Garvey, and George Foster followed with a double down the right field line to score Schmidt for a 2–0 National League lead.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The American Leaguers came right back in the bottom of the first.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] George Brett walked with one out, Don Baylor doubled him in, and Fred Lynn put the AL up 3–2 with a two-out, two-run homer off Steve Carlton.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The NL regained the lead on a bases-loaded sacrifice fly by Parker in the second and an RBI groundout by Dave Winfield in the third.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The AL went back up 5–4 in the bottom of the third when Carl Yastrzemski batted in a run with a single and Chet Lemon scored on a Schmidt error.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The score remained that way until the top of the sixth, when the NL tied it at five on a Winfield double off Mark Clear and an RBI single by Gary Carter.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Pete Rose pinch-hit in and bounced into a double play, then entered the game, replacing Garvey at first and becoming the first player to appear in the All-Star Game at five different positions.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The AL went back up 6–5 in the bottom of the sixth.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Gaylord Perry gave up a leadoff single to Yastrzemski, a double to Darrell Porter, and an RBI single to Mariner Bruce Bochte before leaving in favor of Joe Sambito without retiring a batter.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Sambito pitched the NL out of trouble by getting Reggie Jackson to ground to Lopes at second, who gunned down Porter at the plate.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] After an intentional walk to Roy Smalley to load the bases, Sambito retired Brett and was relieved by Mike LaCoss.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] LaCoss then induced Baylor to hit into a force play end the inning.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In the bottom of the seventh, Jim Rice led off and blooped a double to right with a high bounce off the artificial turf, but was thrown out by Parker as he tried to stretch it into a triple.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Batting for Gary Matthews, Lee Mazzilli tied the score at six in the top of the eighth with an opposite-field homer off Jim Kern, the first pinch-hit home run in MLB All-Star game history.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The AL mounted one last threat in the bottom of the eighth when Brian Downing led off with a crisp single off Bruce Sutter and was sacrificed to second by Bochte.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Sutter walked Jackson intentionally and then struck out Bobby Grich for the second out.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Graig Nettles then lined a single to right, and Downing attempted to score, but once again the arm of Parker claimed another victim.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Fielding the line drive on the first bounce, he fired a perfect strike on the fly to Carter, who blocked Downing's right hand from reaching the plate.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Along with his other assist an inning earlier, this play earned Parker the game's MVP award.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The NL took the lead in the top of the ninth without recording a base hit.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Joe Morgan walked with one out and was balked to second.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Kern walked Parker intentionally, retired Craig Reynolds on a foul pop, but then walked Ron Cey to load the bases.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Ron Guidry came in and walked Mazzilli, forcing in Morgan with the winning run.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In the bottom of the inning, Sutter retired the side, with strikeouts of Rice and Rick Burleson to end the game and earn the win.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] "Pirates' Parker MVP as NL edges AL, 7-6".
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] "All-Star MVP Parker guns down AL, 7-6".
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Player elected to start but declined due to injury.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-seattle-mariners-season] The **1979 Seattle Mariners season** was the franchise's third since its creation.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-seattle-mariners-season] The Mariners ended the season in sixth place in the American League West with a record of 67–95 (.414).
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-seattle-mariners-season] The Mariners hosted the All-Star Game on Tuesday, July 17.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-seattle-mariners-season] The 1979 Major League Baseball All-Star Game was the 50th playing of the midsummer classic between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-seattle-mariners-season] The game was held on July 17, 1979, at the Kingdome, the home of the Mariners.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1979-seattle-mariners-season] The National League defeated the American League, 7–6.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1994-seattle-mariners-season] The **Seattle Mariners 1994 season** was their 18th since the franchise creation, and ended the season finishing third in the American League West, finishing with a 49–63 (.438) record.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1994-seattle-mariners-season] The season was cut short by the player's strike, which began on August 12.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1994-seattle-mariners-season] The Mariners played their final 20 games on the road, due to interior ceiling repairs at the Kingdome; they were 10–1 in August, and won their final six games.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1994-seattle-mariners-season] By Friday, August 12, the Mariners had compiled a 49–63 (.438) record through 112 games and were only two games behind the Texas Rangers for the lead in the four-team AL West.
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1994-seattle-mariners-season] They had scored 569 runs (5.08 per game) and allowed 616 runs (5.50 per game).
[src:1994-seattle-mariners-season/1994-seattle-mariners-season] Slightly more than half of the 162 games scheduled were to be televised this season, with 72 on KSTW and sixteen on Prime Sports Northwest; of those 88 games, 65 were on the road and 23 at home.
